    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.\n\nIn my code, I would like to declare character item types on (byte) strings:\n```cython\ns : str[str] = \"...\"\nfor ch in s:\n    # ch is a `str`, not `Py_UCS4` (the inferred default)\n    ...\n\ns2 : str[cython.Py_UCS4] = \"...\"\nfor ch in s2:\n    # ch is a `Py_UCS4` (explicitly)\n    ...\n\nb: bytes[cython.uchar] = b\"...\"\nfor ch in b:\n    # ch is `unsigned char`, not `char` (the inferred default)\n    ...\n\nb: bytearray[cython.int] = b\"...\"\nfor ch in b:\n    # ch is `int`, not `char` (the inferred default)\n    ...\n```\n\n\n### Describe the solution you'd like.\n\n_No response_\n\n### Describe alternatives you've considered.\n\n_No response_\n\n### Additional context\n\nPython does not allow this:\n```python\n>>> str[str]\nTraceback (most recent call last):\n  File \"<stdin>\", line 1, in <module>\nTypeError: type 'str' is not subscriptable\n```",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I'm not convinced by this.\n* I think places where we deviate from Python typing behaviour have typically caused confusion (although they're mostly for good historic reasons that predate Python typing being defined)\n* It's not obvious to me that this is a unchanging property of the type - you may want different behaviour in different places from the same object.\n* It sort of implies that you shouldn't be able to assign `str[Py_UCS4]` to `str[str]`\n* If we ever go back to evaluated annotations (even if they're deferred) this will probably cause issues (although admittedly we'll probably have issues elsewhere).",
            "created_at": "2026-02-16T19:12:28Z",
            "html_url": "https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/7531#issuecomment-3910164953",
